[{"id":"VR708800","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a rod used in two scenarios labeled trial 1 and trial 2. In trial 1, the rod is held horizontally on a pivot with its left end attached to a sphere of mass 2 M sub 0 and its Â right end attached to a sphere of mass M sub 0. In trial 2, the rod is held horizontally on a pivot with its left end attached to a sphere of mass M sub 0 and its right end attached to a sphere of mass 2 M sub 0. The pivot is placed at the same location in both trials, with the distance from the pivot to the left end being R sub 0, and the distance from the pivot to the right end being 2 R sub 0.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR708800.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A rigid rod of negligible mass is free to rotate on a pivot, as shown in the figures. In experimental Trial <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> a uniform sphere of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 M sub 0\"><math alttext=\"2 M sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> is attached to the rod with its center a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R sub 0\"><math alttext=\"R sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> to the left of the pivot, and a second uniform sphere of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M sub 0\"><math alttext=\"M sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> is attached to the rod with its center a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2 R sub 0\"><math alttext=\"2 R sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> to the right of the pivot. The radii of the spheres are negligible compared to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R sub 0\"><math alttext=\"R sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>. The rod is held horizontally and then released. In Trial <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> the spheres are switched as shown, and the rod is again held horizontally and released. Compare the rotational motion of the rod-spheres system in the two trials.</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1 colwidth:45\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:130\"/><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:130\"/><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Trial 1</th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">Trial 2</th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Remains at rest</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Remains at rest</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">B</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Remains at rest</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Begins to rotate</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">C</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Begins to rotate</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Remains at rest</td></tr><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">D</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\">Begins to rotate</td><td class=\"entry colname:col3\">Begins to rotate</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR708800_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p clas